  <main class="wrap">
    <h1>What Actually Makes a College Fight Song “Hype”?</h1>
    <p class="deck">College fight songs mapped by musical speed and lyrical aggression.</p>

    <div class="chart">
      <iframe
        title="What Actually Makes a College Fight Song Hype?"
        aria-label="Scatter plot"
        id="datawrapper-chart-8OzhT"
        src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/8OzhT/2/"
        scrolling="no"
        frameborder="0"
        height="720"
        data-external="1">
      </iframe>
    </div>

    <p class="callout">
      Fight songs are designed to energize crowds, but not all of them do it the same way. This chart maps songs by
      how fast they are and how aggressively their lyrics repeat traditional hype tropes. Together, these dimensions
      reveal four distinct styles of hype.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>How hype styles extend beyond the song</h2>
    <p>
      Fight songs shape how hype is expressed, but they exist within broader home-field environments.
      To explore whether hype styles tend to appear in more intimidating settings, we combine recent home win rates (2021–2025)
      and stadium capacity into a standardized measure of stadium difficulty.
      The distribution below shows how Big Ten schools (<strong>n = 16 programs</strong>) in each hype style are spread across
      low-, medium-, and high-difficulty home environments.
    </p>

    <div class="chart">
      <iframe
        title="Stadium Difficulty by Fight Song Hype Style"
        aria-label="100% stacked bars"
        id="datawrapper-chart-J8TFR"
        src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/J8TFR/1/"
        scrolling="no"
        frameborder="0"
        height="520"
        data-external="1">
      </iframe>
    </div>

    <p class="callout">
      <strong>Takeaway:</strong> Aggressive and hybrid hype styles appear more often in difficult home environments, while speed-driven
      styles skew toward easier ones.
    </p>

    <details>
      <summary>How the analysis works</summary>
      <ul>
        <li>Fight song data: FiveThirtyEight (tempo + lyrical tropes).</li>
        <li>Hype styles defined by dataset medians (BPM and trope count).</li>
        <li>Stadium difficulty combines standardized home win rate (2021–2025) and stadium capacity.</li>
        <li>Secondary analysis focuses on Big Ten programs.</li>
      </ul>
    </details>

    <div class="footer">
